<section xml:id="section-forms-summary-elem-nilp">

<title>Elementary nilpotent form</title>

<paragraphs><title>What</title><p>
	<me>
		\inv{P} A P
		= \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \\ \amp \ddots \amp \ddots \\ \amp  \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
	</me>.
</p></paragraphs>

<paragraphs><title>When</title><p>
	Matrix <m>A</m> is nilpotent, with <m>A^{n-1} \ne \zerovec</m>.
</p></paragraphs>

<paragraphs><title>How</title><p>
	Choose an index <m>j</m> such that the <m>\nth[j]</m> column of <m>A^{n-1}</m> is nonzero.
	Then take the columns of <m>P</m> to be
	<md><mrow>
		\uvec{p}_1 \amp = \uvec{e}_j, \amp
		\uvec{p}_2 \amp = A\uvec{e}_j, \amp
		\uvec{p}_3 \amp = A^2\uvec{e}_j, \amp
		\amp\dotsc, \amp
		\uvec{p}_n \amp = A^{n-1}\uvec{e}_j
	</mrow></md>,
	where <m>\uvec{e}_j</m> is the <m>\nth[j]</m> standard basis vector.
</p></paragraphs>

<paragraphs><title>Result</title><p>
	Always exactly of the form described at the beginning of this section.
</p></paragraphs>

</section>
